I have a worthy challenge for you. I'm going to give you a URL pointing at a design document for a digital circuit written in a unique descriptive language. The problem is there is no formal description for this language, just an example. I would like you To create documentation for the language implied by the example. The example is https://gtoal.com/vectrex/joystick/netlist.txt

It said:

A fun reverse-engineering task. Let me fetch the netlist and study it.

Done — the spec is at docs/netlist-language.md (untracked in the repo; move it wherever you like).

The language in a nutshell: a line-oriented netlist format with exactly three constructs, used in declare-before-use order:

1. pinout <Type> … end <Type> defines a package type as pin <number> = <name> [= alias…] lines. Names are wildly permissive — they can start with digits or +/- (3.3v, -5v), contain dots (SPI0.MOSI), and end with a prime for active-low (CS'). Repeating a name across pins (eight pins named 0v) makes it a rail class: any like-named pin satisfies a connection.
2. package <Type> <Instance>… instantiates one or more named instances.
3. circuit <Name> … end <Name> lists connections of the form Inst.Pin -> Inst.Pin. The arrow is documentation only (source on the left, sink on the right); electrically each statement just merges two pins into a net, and nets merge transitively. ; chains related connections on one line, used for current paths like B1 -> Opto0.Collector ; Opto0.Emitter -> 0v.

Two inferences worth calling out, since you asked for the language implied by the example rather than just a transcription:

- Pin references split at the first dot. PI.SPI0.CE0 is instance PI, pin SPI0.CE0 — which forces the rule that instance names may not contain dots while pin names may.
- The example's own bugs were the best evidence. The end tags mismatch three times out of five (pinout PI … end MCP42010, etc.), the package line declares Opto1–Opto8 while the circuit uses Opto0–Opto7, and there are two genuine copy-paste wiring errors (RYLo.Mid/LYLo.Mid connected where the X-axis trimpots RXLo.Mid/LXLo.Mid were clearly intended, leaving those wipers floating). I documented each as errata paired with the validation rule a checker should enforce — mismatched-end detection, undeclared/unused instance checks, and unconnected-pin warnings, the last of which would have caught the real wiring bug.

The spec also includes an EBNF grammar, the net-merging semantics, the # X.SO -> unconnected convention for deliberately floating pins, and a self-contained miniature example exercising every feature. One asymmetry I judged intentional rather than a bug: Y-axis trimpots are wired +5v -> Right but X-axis ones +5v -> Left, which reads as a record of physical mounting orientation.

